reasoning_content:
Now I understand the issue. In the `generate_mch_khz_1dot25` function in `pmch.c`, after the parallel encoding threads complete, the `respEncode` notifiedFIFO is destroyed by going out of scope, but any remaining elements in the FIFO are not properly cleaned up.

Looking at the thread-pool.h file, I can see that when a notifiedFIFO is destroyed or goes out of scope, any remaining elements should be freed using `delNotifiedFIFO_elt()`. However, in the current implementation, the `respEncode` FIFO is simply destroyed when it goes out of scope without cleaning up any remaining elements.

The issue is in this section of the code:

```c
  // Wait all other threads finish to process
  while (nbEncode) {
    notifiedFIFO_elt_t *res = pullTpool(&respEncode, proc->threadPool);
    if (res == NULL)
      break; // Tpool has been stopped
    delNotifiedFIFO_elt(res);
    nbEncode--;
  }
```

The problem is that `pullTpool()` might return NULL for various reasons (pool stopped, etc.), but there could still be elements remaining in the FIFO that haven't been processed. These elements would leak memory.

Additionally, after the while loop completes, there might be elements still in the FIFO that need to be cleaned up before the FIFO itself is destroyed.

The fix is to ensure that all remaining elements in the `respEncode` FIFO are properly cleaned up before the function returns, even if `pullTpool()` returns NULL.

Let me implement the fix:

```c
  // Wait all other threads finish to process
  while (nbEncode) {
    notifiedFIFO_elt_t *res = pullTpool(&respEncode, proc->threadPool);
    if (res == NULL)
      break; // Tpool has been stopped
    delNotifiedFIFO_elt(res);
    nbEncode--;
  }

  // Clean up any remaining elements in the FIFO to prevent memory leaks
  notifiedFIFO_elt_t *remaining;
  while ((remaining = pollNotifiedFIFO(&respEncode)) != NULL) {
